            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Heather Clarke\u2019s life is seasoned with the sharp tang of risk and the comforting warmth of a well-run dining room. Raised in the manicured quiet of Marin County, her childhood was one of structured expectations; her parents, a lawyer and an architect, valued stability over passion. For Heather, however, true comfort was found in the vibrant, controlled chaos of the restaurants her family frequented on special occasions. She was fascinated by the ballet of servers, the hushed commands from the kitchen, and the symphony of happy patrons. This fascination led her to Cal Poly\u2019s Hospitality Management program, a practical choice that felt like a rebellion.\n\nHer career began in the trenches of corporate hotel restaurants, where she honed her skills in management and finance but felt stifled by the lack of soul. The turning point came in her late thirties. Freshly divorced from a man who never understood her obsession with the industry, she was the front-of-house manager at a stuffy downtown establishment where she worked alongside Marco, a brilliant, hot-headed chef. They bonded over late-night talks, dreaming of a place that was theirs\u2014one that valued seasonal ingredients and a happy staff as much as profit margins.\n\nPooling their life savings and convincing a regular to invest, they took a massive leap and opened \"Cypress,\" a Cal-Mediterranean bistro in a cozy Hayes Valley storefront. For the last decade, Cypress has been her life. Her 0.8-mile walk from her condo to the restaurant is a cherished daily ritual, a time to mentally prep for the day. Her life is the restaurant: managing payroll, placating demanding diners, celebrating staff birthdays, and tasting Marco\u2019s latest creations. Her staff is her family, and her regulars are her community.\n\nNow at 49, with Cypress a beloved neighborhood institution, Heather dreams of something new: balance. She aspires to finally take a real two-week vacation, perhaps to Spain, and to mentor a young manager to eventually take her place. Her ultimate goal is to see Cypress thrive without her constant presence, allowing her to finally enjoy the city she has worked so hard to serve."
